text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I can't load the description of how to match A>B in the presence of XBL into my head.  Given <details><summary/><div></div></details>, and <template><content includes=summary /><div><content /></div></template>, does "details>div" match the light-dom <div>, the shadow <div>, or both?

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: off-hand, i dunno, i've paged all that out to long-term storage :-)

author: 1f8387eb43f131d7c309a90a4e36b5cb
text: I wish you'd been writing in a proper algorithmic style back then.  Expressing an algorithm as a series of "otherwise" clauses in a paragraph is confusing.

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: i don't recall that being especially difficult though, let me look

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: ok so we're given <details><summary/><div></div></details> and <template><content includes=summary /><div><content/></div></template>

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: ok, there are two potential <div>s that could match

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: let's look at the first one, in the bound element dom

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: it has a details parent, so it definitely matches, irrespective of xbl

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: now let's look at the other one

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: its parent is a <template>, so that's what X is in the second paragraph...

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: ok so "allow-selectors-through" is true and we assume there's no other binding applying

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: so X becomes the bound element

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: what is the bound element here, <details>?

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: then yes, both <div>s match that selector.

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: was it intended that canvas.getContext() cache a null return value from "Return a new object for contextId"? or was it assumed that it would never fail if the context is supported by the UA?

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: (guessing it wasn't intended to receive null as a return value, since null usually isn't considered "a new object")

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: as you say, null is not a new object :-)

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: (and firefox just crashed, so a minute of thrashing to restart it...)

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: should the abstract "return a new object" algorithm never return null?

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: getContext just doesn't seem to describe what happens on error--it seems like the "primary context" should also not be set on error

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: (webgl returns null on error, which is why I care--it doesn't seem like that's valid)

author: 353fa4cc248867e98de9cab7d122c320
text: the problem is for webgl context creation should be async

author: 353fa4cc248867e98de9cab7d122c320
text: since it's heavyweight and can fail

author: 353fa4cc248867e98de9cab7d122c320
text: 2d context creation is assumed to be pretty lightweight and won't reasonably fail

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: they do have "context lost"/"context restored" events, but they're used later

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: i'm trying to convince them to do something saner, but that's hard to do when I can't tell what getContext actually wants them to do :)

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: IMO: getContext should propagate exceptions from context creation, clear the "primary context" on exception if it was just set, and prohibit null as a return value entirely

author: 353fa4cc248867e98de9cab7d122c320
text: what would you return in the case of a context initialization failure?

author: 353fa4cc248867e98de9cab7d122c320
text: so you'd have to block the call until you knew the context was ready

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: but I can't recommend that to webgl when getContext itself doesn't support it

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: it already has to do that

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: since webgl returns null if the context can't be created; now it would just throw an exception instead

author: 353fa4cc248867e98de9cab7d122c320
text: right. which is unfortunate for webgl but orthogonal to your concern

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: from talking with them this isn't totally set in stone, which is why I'm trying to nudge this towards something better before it is

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: (which is why I'm nagging hixie on IRC :)

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6: the abstract "return a new object" algorithm should never return null, it should return a new object. :-)

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6: how can there be an error?

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: webgl context creation can fail; it doesn't know if it can create a context until you try

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: i don't understand how it could possibly fail

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: you just get an object back

author: 06cb330920ae58e1614c9145d983b3d6
text: creating the context creates the OS OpenGL context; that may fail

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: that's the UAs problem, it shouldn't expose such failures to web code

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: web pages aren't going to be able to do any thing useful if getContext() returns null

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: anyway, gotta go for dinner, will be back in a few hours if you want to discuss further.

text: Has anyone heard about any kind of management system for vim plugins/scripts?

text: I'm thinking along the lines of CPAN for perl.

author: d711e4c8dbc8ccb10d953ab45ad18a36

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: I've started looking at the Vimball script and GetLatestVimScripts plugin.

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: Well, downloading them is easy enough, but sometimes I don't want to track down the versions.

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: and some plugins are starting to need other plugins.

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: Occasionally one plugin will need slightly different installation procedures, rather than just untarring/unzipping.

author: d711e4c8dbc8ccb10d953ab45ad18a36
text: i made a python script to compare versions - used BeautifulSoup and was like 20 lines or so...

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: Did it pull in any dependencies?

author: d711e4c8dbc8ccb10d953ab45ad18a36
text: no... how would it do that... it checked versions

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: Have you seen the GetLatestVimScripts plugin?

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: I've gotten spoiled by package management systems like Debian's apt, or Gentoo's emerge.

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: And those systems are slow to adopt vim plugins.

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: And even if people do write ebuilds and debs you'll still have users wanting a different setup for themselves.

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: I just thought Vimball and GetLatestVimScripts might be part of a larger initiative.

author: 082b9bc1657b43db3a0e0b1b0066d690
text: I also thought about Makefiles for doing some of this and then I found: http://www.a-a-p.org/

text: so in other words, everyone should get rw oplock for that file

author: 0eb40418ab835cda37dc49b920b73981
text: unless we're talking about a db/file that is the backend for an application with revision control of some sort

author: 0eb40418ab835cda37dc49b920b73981
text: whats advantage do you get from everyone having rw at the same time?

author: 932b433e8e456828a538f138916e4fc4
text: I would imagine the main concern is that it violates the contract made by previous specifications that class='' imparts no particular meaning above providing an identification string to hang, e.g., CSS off.

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: @role (in the XHTML2 WD) will have similar issues if any future revisions to the spec want to add values in the global namespace

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: HTML4 says it's for "For general purpose processing by user agents" in addition to being a style hook, which I'd interpret as saying it can be used for whatever arbitrary things the UA wants

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: @profile directly references it, does it not?

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: (though it'd be valid to ignore what HTML4 says and only consider the implied agreement between real UAs and authors, that class is just used for styles)

author: 932b433e8e456828a538f138916e4fc4
text: That may be a point for disagreement then. Worth exploring I think.

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: FF3's microformat support would also be a non-styling use of class

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: and that won't use @profile, as too many documents with f don't use the @profile

text: I'm just looking at charset sniffing now

author: 73c8ec97fe210f482d81a5f04e5e6642
text: currently it is defined imperatively: go forward one byte, if it's this then goto step 1, otherwise step 2...

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: trying to work out how to implement things without using regex when given like that can get rather complex

author: 73c8ec97fe210f482d81a5f04e5e6642
text: eh? you mean if I give you a regular expression you don't know what to do with it, or what?

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: I mean trying to implement a complex regular expression without using regular expressions can be hard to work out

author: 73c8ec97fe210f482d81a5f04e5e6642
text: well, not really; regular expressions can be transformed into code mechanically

author: a924fb58d2c25874322f4e5126f608b9
text: The regular expressions have to be created from prose first, though

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: Would BNF be easier to understand and less line-noise-like than regular expressions, but still work about the same?

text: you would create definitions for commonly used bits

author: 73c8ec97fe210f482d81a5f04e5e6642
text: more like the EBNF in the XML spec

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: I have a preference of ABNF, personally

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: still doesn't really know how to parse URIs without using regular expressions, when you don't know how many parts of the URI you have

author: 73c8ec97fe210f482d81a5f04e5e6642
text: you mean like optional query parameters or port numbers?

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: I can think of ways of doing it, but all very expensive

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: The W3C license may (or may not) provide additional rights, but it doesn't take away any rights.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: I'm not sure I understand "Whats more important, and largely unaddressed, is the fact that the domain of documents which can be serialized as HTML5 and as XHTML5 do not observe a proper super/subset relationship." as XHTML5 would never use text/html

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: There are documents that I can only express in XHTML.  There are documents that I can only express in HTML.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: the point of the question was that from now on you either use HTML or XHTML and that which you use depends on the media type you declare

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: in other words, I get to pick something and later find out that there are things I can't do.

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: if one was a proper subset of the other, I would be fine with that.  But that is not the case.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: phrasing your objection to XML well-formedness madness as an objection to that question makes it hard for me to address feedback

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: this does not appear to be a problem with the FAQ, but rather with intrinsic properties of HTML and XHTML as things stand today

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: why "stand today"?  HTML5 defines some forward thinking things...

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: but we can't tackle the XML issue

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: then, IMO, (X)HTML5 will not "finally put an end to the XHTML as text/html" debate.

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: yes, it would seem that the issues are separable, but I suggest that they are not.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: though, to be honest, some have suggested we can, by defining an "XML Application" spec that basically defines XML5 and says you have to follow XML 1.0 until you hit a well-formedness error and then you follow XML5...

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: XML5, as you have started to define it, would put an end to the HTML/XHTML debate.  Of course it would create an XML1/XML5 debate... but that might not be bad.

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: hmm, I guess I'll just leave that unchanged because I'm not sure what to say instead

text: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d: Should it have any meaning?

text: Otherwise we end up having different rules to find character encoding in XML and XHTML

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: basically, but the document would be non-conforming if meta-charset does not match the encoding an XML parser would associate with the document.

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: And would it do anything if it was different?

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: The only at all possible issue is authors thinking it does something

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: it would allow me to sent the exact same bytes on my weblog as text/html as application/xhtml+xml.

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: Can't you just use the charset parameter on the Content-Type header and not have meta@charset at all?

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: the short answer is yes, but the long answer is that content-type is unreliable.

author: a11aabeeceeae6b8cb5d12ea06b56554
text: How so? When is it ignored except when it looks like a feed?

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: Periodically, I have people complain about my weblog, and it turns out that they are viewing a cached xhtml page served to them as text/html.

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: As opera and firefox move towards the parsing that html5 defines (and is implemented by webkit), my pages look reasonably fine when served as text/html (minus, for the moment, the display of svg).

author: a480104b0e570389c6f4284a88c7cd9d
text: And I actually have versions of my page that deal with browsers (including IE8) that don't yet support html5's parsing rules.

text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I'm writing <select required> checking for the validator and I the spec seems quite clear but I want to doublecheck

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: the following should be valid, right?

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: and the following should not be?

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: i assume we're ignoring the <option> here, right? attribute-wise?

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: or should i check the option requirements too

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: there are not requirements on the option in that case, as far as I can see

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: so, no, anyway, you don't need to check the option requirements for that first case

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: I just meant is is valid as far as the select goes

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: in the first case, the option has to have a value="" if its contents aren't "".

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: the second one is invalid, indeed

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: so yes, valid and not valid

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: the first might want to emit a warning that the author probably forgot to give the text of the placeholder label option

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: dunno how much linting you're doing

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: but now I do think I'm misunderstanding something

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: which ish, how do you give the text of the placeholder label option

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: in the label="" or textContent of the <option>

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: but the spec says, "if the value of the first option element in the select element's list of options (if any) is the empty string, and that option element's parent node is the select element (and not an optgroup element), then that option is the select element's placeholder label option."

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: should that be "is *not* the empty string"?

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: (when you get back), so it seems like maybe it should say that the value attribute is empty (or not specified), but the option must have textContent

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: because, unless I'm missing something, I don't see how the option element can serve as an actual placeholder label option if the "value of the option element" (= "the value of the value attribute, if there is one, or the textContent of the element, if there isn't") has to be the empty string

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: in other words, the current spec text seems to require the following to be reported as invalid

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: because it must have a placeholder label option, but the value of the first option element is not the empty string, so it does not have a placeholder label option

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: right, if you have required in that case you also have to have <option value="">label</option>

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: because otherwise there's no point having required="" -- it'd be required anyway

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: you can't _not_ give a value in that case

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: so marking it required="" is worthless

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: right, but that's not what the spec seems to say

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: in that case, it doesn't have a placeholder label option, and it must have a placeholder label option, right?

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: it doesn't have one because the value of the first option is "1", so the first option is not a placeholder label option

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: but the first option has no value attribute

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: the value of the second option is 1

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: i mean the value of the first option is "Choose one of the following"

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: I think I see what the purpose of this is now

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: you probably want the validator to notice when the first one have a value="non-empty" and give a distinct error than the case where it is simply missing a value="" (but has textContent, as opposed to <option label="choose one of the following">, which would be fine)

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: because the error message would be confusing otherwise

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: so sorry if I'm being daft here, but if the following is not OK, what should it be changed to?

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: it's fine, from a validation point of view

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: OK, but what I'm getting at is, the spec currently says that for an option to be a placeholder label option, its "value" must be the empty string

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: where "value" is defined as "the value of the value attribute, if there is one, or the textContent of the element, if there isn't"

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: (hm, we should probably strip spaces before and after the textContent, for sanity, so that omitting the </option> in the case above doesn't matter, but that's another story)

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: so that would seem to mean that <option value="">label</option> cannot be a placeholder label option

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: OK but the "value" of the option is non-empty

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: the value is the value of the value attribute, if there is one

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: this stuff is inane, and i make enough mistakes that half the time your questions are just pointing out mistakes i made :-)

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: not sure that's true, but thanks for saying it :)

author: 1f58faf0d058f303f30239a369808167
text: I wish there was a way to do

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: so why not have the spec say that for <select required>, its first option child must have a value="" attribute specified?

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: we could do that, but in the case of <option label=".."/> it's a bit ugly to require an otherwise redundant value="" as well

text: 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: however, the spec doesn't specify when the parser has to yield to let timeouts and intervals run

author: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9
text: as far as I can tell, the parser only needs to yield when it sees a </script> end tag

author: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9
text: and otherwise, yielding is up to the implementation

author: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9
text: which makes me wonder if Web compat requires some level of discretionary yielding

text: there are libraries that poll the dom every X ms for an element

author: 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46
text: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e: it's because namespaces are optional in dom3 core

text: 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: is the compat requirement that parser must yield every Y ms or is the compate requirement that whenever the parser yields for the CSS formatter, intervals must fire, too?

text: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: for the library point of view it just wants to get the element as soon as it's available

text: 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: yeah, but is it only to keep up with layout?

author: 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46
text: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: no i think it's mainly to have e.g. buttons do something before the page has finished loading

author: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9
text: 73eaf221abca1b8244e34b0b9e76ac46: isn't that keeping up with layout?

author: b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9
text: in Gecko, the yielding from the parser depends on the user event queue

author: a8f9454c20902641f25daa98ea52073f
text: I have a catalyst 4507 switch that i just configured. Currently connected to a another switch via fiber. Everything is working ok. All ports are assigned to vlan1 after setting the default gateway I was able to use the ports. Now I want to be able to create vlans on the switch. My goal is to create 3 vlans and move ports into them. However when doing so I loose the ability of communicating with ports when outside of the vlan.

author: cc9aab29ebea79d6850e644dfe75f241
text: traffic must be routed between VLANs.  your switch can do it, but then it becomes a router.  to accomplish this, create a VLAN interface for each vlan ('interface Vlan 2') and assign it an IP address.  then use this address as the default gateway for hosts on that VLAN.

author: a8f9454c20902641f25daa98ea52073f
text: Catfive: after assining the vlan interface to an ip do I have to do anything with ip routing?

author: cc9aab29ebea79d6850e644dfe75f241
text: you can configure 'no shutdown' on the VLAN interface and 'ip routing' globally, just to make sure things are enabled.

author: a8f9454c20902641f25daa98ea52073f
text: Catfive: so it is necessary to use the ip rotuing option globally

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: just waiting on html4diffs and h:tml to be updated now

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: I just now updated the h:tml draft and waiting for the cvs commit to complete

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: so now we're just waiting on Anne

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: I asked him to update earlier today, so hopefully he'll do it whenever he gets up

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: I asked him to update ~5 hours ago

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: even though it is an arbitrary milestone, I am for some reason very excited about publishing

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: I think the biggest positive effect of WD publication is that it gets documents a lot wider attention than just editor's-draft publication does

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: at least as far as W3C publication goes

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: and for a certain period of time, at least

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: in the context of HTML5, I have not seen it result in a higher level of technical review

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: though it does get some sort of attention in the tech press

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: yeah, the downside of that is that one of the first questions all the media people seem to ask every time W3C publishes and HTML5 WD is that, "OK, so when will HTML5 be done?" question

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: to which it seems to me the only proper response is to try to get them to see that they're asking the wrong question

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: then we can just point to the charter and indicate that the next milestone is Last Call

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: which is on schedule, so long as we can invent time travel technology in the next few months

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: the ietf guys argued that websocket would get wider review if we went through the ietf, but so far all the useful feedback i've received has been either off-list or on the whatwg list

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: similar to how it was argued that html5 would get more review if we went through the w3c

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: looks to me like the standards organisations are out of date in terms of what gets wider useful feedback :-)

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I sent useful feedback on the ietf list... I think

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: i think everything you said on the list you first said on the adam/you/me thread we had

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: and adam and you would have reviewed the spec anyway, regardless of whether we went w3c, whatwg, or ietf

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: nah, I pointed out the reverse cross-protocol problem on the list first, then discussed it with you on IRC, then on the email thread with Adam

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: I would like to say I would have given that feedback anyway but I only thought of it due to people questioning the handshake

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: standards organizations are out of date in a lot of ways.. I guess until we actually work on coming up with viable alternative, we are stuck with what we got, and hopefully at least we can (or have) managed to get some improvements made

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: I mean, I might have still had the thought

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: my most successful standard i think has been pingback, which didn't involve a standards organisation at all

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: it's not clear to me how to make a good standards org

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2: so it's not clear to me that we _need_ an alternative

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: I think the existence of the Web Sockets discussion at IETF has helped to changed the IETF culture for the better

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: all the existing ones either come down to pay-to-play voting or dictatorship by an elite oligarchy, if you push hard enough

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: i think the oligarchy mechanism is the only one that truly works, but it only works so long as the oligarchy has the respect of the implementors

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: and i think it pretty much stops having the respect as soon as there's a process in place, because a process forcibly distances the oligarchy from the implementors

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: part of the problem the w3c and ietf both have is that they try to solve too many problems at once

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: having multiple focus areas is a huge red flag for a std org imho

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: I think the implementors issue is something that the Web Sockets work has helped to raise awareness about in the IETF

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: oligarchy can work with the right oligarchs

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: and so long as it does not get overwhelmed with legitimacy disputes

author: a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2
text: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: the awareness being that it is risky to develop a spec without also working hard to get implementor buy-in during the spec-development process

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: IETF and W3C try to have consensus/voting as the front line decision-making tool, with escalation to a dictator/oligarchy

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: sometimes I wonder if the other way around would work better

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: of course, in the HTML WG we kinda have a sandwich

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: we just have three tiers of <span>abort the

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: we just have three tiers of oligarchy

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: I guess layers at least limit the damage that can be done by any one layer going off the rails

author: 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e
text: each tier being further removed from the issues, leading to more and more random resolutions as an issue is escalated ;-)

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: I find I need to have a lot more familiarity with the issues than I think I should have to for my role

text: (I guess tree is not a good word to describe it though)

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: b406b22e31ce6e541c3754a7214cec1c, it's the best short word so far

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: and it might confuse people who are into this: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supertree

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: "subtree" sounds confusing because you'd think it's a tree with branches, when acually it's just a list

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: has a book where "ancestor" includes the node itself, and "proper ancestor" doesn't

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: subtree is standard when referring to the tree formed by the descendants of a node, but not when referring to the chain of ancestors, I think

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: we'd use supertree for the the ancestor part

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: "supertree" sounds confusing because you'd think it's a tree with branches, when actually it's just a list

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: would probably assume the supertree is the largest tree that contains the given node (i.e. the one rooted at the most distant ancestor)

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: If "ancestor" is already defined to exclude the node itself, "ancestor or self" doesn't sound too bad (it's a bit ugly but short and clear), or maybe "inclusive ancestor"

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: inclusive ancestor sounds rather clear and works a bit better in this context

author: efcfdc75e9299f9082b85c6f181b106f
text: As someone who has no idea what you guys are talking about, "ancestor and self" is much easier to understand than "inclusivve ancestor"

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: true enough, but understanding this term is the least of your worries when you implement range

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: The term (and "ancestor" by itself) should be linked to a precise definition, so I guess it's not too bad if people have to click the link to find what you mean

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: (It'd be worse if they thought they knew what it meant, so they didn't check the definition, but actually had the wrong idea)

author: efcfdc75e9299f9082b85c6f181b106f
text: "Let's name it something nobody will be certain to understand and force them to look for the proper definition"

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: Then you just define "Concept #382: A concept #53 that is the target concept #53 or a concept #197 of it", and "Concept #197: A concept #53 that is a concept #382 of the target concept #53 but is not the target concept #53 itself", etc

author: efcfdc75e9299f9082b85c6f181b106f
text: And throw in some false links to make sure they're paying attention and not just clicking along.

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: Darien do you know stuff about mysql_unbuffered_query?

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: Alterin_: I know stuff about unbuffered queries as a general topic

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: Darien should we use it when possible?

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: Alterin_: it can save memory, so it's not a bad idea

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: or it has a down side?

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: the downside of unbuffered queries is that you can't do random access

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: you have to operate on the first record, then the second, then the third, and so on

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: what do you mean by random acess?

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: well, you can't use record 23, then 14, then 39, then 82, then 12

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: but if you're going to do that anyway, you can decrease memory usage dramatically, and increase performance because you don't have to wait

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: what if i retreive only one line?

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: well then it makes no difference whatsoever

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: normally what happens if you select (for example) 500 rows, is MySQL will get those 500 rows out of the database and then send them to you all at once

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: with unbuffered queries, it starts getting rows out of the database, and as soon as it has the first one it sends it to you

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: and then when it has the second, it sends it, and then the third, and so on

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: so you don't have to wait until MySQL has 500 rows, then wait until it sends them all to you over the network

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: Darien what do you do for a livin?

text: Alterin_: support analyst for a company that makes medical imaging management systems

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: Darien is count much faster than a normal select?

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: so it's better to make a count first and a normal select latter

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: is we want first to verify if it exists

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: SELECT TRUE FROM user WHERE username='foo' AND password='blah'

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: assuming you have an index on (username,password) then your entire users table is in memory already

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: and so you never have to hit the disk

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: we get if its banned, and other stats so that we can show them right away

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: but it can be no user so we are trying to get that info for nothing

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: and then a get for the info

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: ok, let me put it this way

author: f6b127e38214e484df709cbee84fa242
text: In Soviet Russia, MySQL queries YOU

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: doing A is faster than B

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: doing A then B is slower than doing eithe rone

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: especially if you can do one query that does both

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: so A+B in one is always better

author: fa09e159d3aa53d95b8041a384a5fad9
text: even if you are trying to get data that doesn't exist

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: because if you do A and it doesn't exist, its' just as fast as doing B and it doesn't exist

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: because it's only using the index anyway

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: so it's doing the same work in both queries

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: if it scans the index and doesn't find the row, it's not going to hit the disk, it'll just give up

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: if it scans the index and finds the row, then it doesn't have to scan the index again on the next query

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: the general rule is that the fewer SQL queries you're doing, the better

author: 46b908401111ea4fd08e643e2db3534f
text: because then you also avoid a round-trip to the server and back, plus the overhead of parsing the SQL query, locking the table for read, and so on

text: Star rating widgets are often interactive, so you can click on the nth star to submit a rating of n

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: so <progress> won't work there - what's a good alternative?

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: Rating: <a href=vote?1><img src=onstar alt='Current rating: 2 out of 3. Submit your vote: 1' title='Vote 1/3'></a><a href=vote?2><img src=onstar alt=2 title='Vote 2/3'></a><a href=vote?3><img src=offstar alt=3 title='Vote 3/3'></a>

author: ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee
text: logically speaking it's a input type="range"

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: yeah and once submitted it's converted into <meter>

author: edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e
text: once the CSS/XBL story actually works for form controls

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: still doesn't like depending on technologies that don't exist yet

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: best current way would probably be to put a click event handler on every star

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: (since you probably want to submit the rating in some ajaxy way)

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: or you could make them <input type="image"> and have an onsubmit handler on the form do the async submission

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: If it's done with multiple images, I'm wondering what suitable alt text should be, since it needs to convey the value of each star and the current rating, and there are ~5 separate alt attributes to spread the text across

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: logically, it's an <input type="range" min="1" max="5">

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: but XBL binding that to look right - good luck

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: I guess input type="number" might be more appropriate

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: you could use alt to represent the state and "title" on each star to indicate what clicking it will do

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: It should be possible to write conforming HTML5 that works in legacy browsers

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: in which case you can't use new <input> types or XBL

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c: The issue (or at least the one I'm pretending to care about) is that you then have multiple images conveying a single piece of information (the current rating), and alt is defined to only be about the information conveyed by a single image

author: ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee
text: could also be a fieldset of radio buttons

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: <form onsubmit="changeRating(event)"><input type="image" alt="" title="set rating to 1/5"><input type="image" alt="2/5"....>

author: 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c
text: that might not give good results in a screen reader though

author: ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c
text: You should be able to vote for the current rating too (where 'current rating' is determined by other voters)

author: ef6f2287bae00ba79475fbf56c2b6fee
text: <fieldset><legend>Rating: 2 out of 5</legend><input type="image" alt="Set rating to 1 out of 5"><img alt=""><input type="image" alt="Set rating to 3 out of 5">...</fieldset>

text: "The URI generic syntax for authority also includes a deprecated userinfo subcomponent ([RFC3986], Section 3.2.1) for including user authentication information in the URI. The userinfo subcomponent (and its "@" delimiter) MUST NOT be used in an "http" URI. text: Meeting: Cascading Style Sheets (CSS) Working Group Teleconference

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: zakim, remind us in 8 hours to go home

author: 4e63bbbffbcaf12608512401eaf11240
text: I have made the request to generate http://www.w3.org/2009/03/04-css-minutes.html a9b326df4e6da61c5b6f5e1058be83a2

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: Anne: several comments have been made

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: Anne: Dean Jackson has proposed changes in aspect-ratio syntax

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: Dan Jackson asked for syntax changes in some queries

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: Anne: I would be fine dropping the features at risk, and keep orientation unchanged

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: Anne: the use case is to have a DOM interface to the orientation

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: portrait or landscape is much more useful

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: steve: is there a square pixel issue involved?

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: Anne: s/the use case/the use case for degrees/

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: Chris: If you're using it for games and things, then you also want to know the tilt, the acceleration, etc. Just make another API

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 104bc19e5513cba4eba2d18c7a704a01: the use case for device-aspect-ration is weak

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: Steve: In that case you'd want landscape/portrait in addition to the orientation angle

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: 104bc19e5513cba4eba2d18c7a704a01: the use case for device-* is weak

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 104bc19e5513cba4eba2d18c7a704a01: but we implement both aspect-ratio and device-aspect-ratio

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: I could see a stylesheht that gave 4 columns for a 16:9 landscape and 3 for 4:3

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: one use case is having more columns if the display is wide

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0: in that case you care about the width

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: Not if you're doing a presentation that scales to fill the space

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: steve: if I have several images, I could select the right one to fill the sceen

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: steve: I thought we went through this in great detail, why are we discussin this?

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0vk: apple has proposed a syntax change

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 104bc19e5513cba4eba2d18c7a704a01: given that we now support exact matching, we should stick to our current syntax

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: yes, trying to match on a float is liable to error

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4 is skeptical that aspect-ratio is useful

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: you can use it to select a different video, widescreen vs fullscreen

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0: device-aspect-ratio would be useful for videos too

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: Media queries are used for more than just CSS

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: Chris: Mozilla and Opera both implement it

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: common industry use is ratio - 16:9, 16:10, 4:3 not 1.623

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: so we have implementations in firefox, opera and webkit

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: RESOLVED: Keep aspect-ratio and device-aspect-ratio, no changes to syntax

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0vk: some editoral comments, some comments on tty

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0vk: we don't clarify what px unit means for tty devices

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0vk: that clarification should possibly go into the Values and Units draft

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: there was one about malformed queries

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: chrisl: is there as disposition of comments?

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0vk: I can add the new issues to the previous disposition of comments

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 104bc19e5513cba4eba2d18c7a704a01: what's the issue with the formal grammar

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4: so, it seems we currently can't take all grammars in all CSS specs, concatinate them and have something valid comes out

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: steve: the formal grammar is only a hint

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: befddef7b56a6caf71fa21f2235a8111: there are things that cannot easily be expressed in formal grammars

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: szilles: do we say anywhere what the goal of the formal grammars are?

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4: HTML5 writes it out in prose

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: The spec could state that, due to grammar overrides in the prose, the grammar is not sufficient by itself for creating a parser

author: ac3b293515e969dace7717d9104ad079
text: The snapshots could collect together the 2.1 grammar plus the patches defined in each odule, to goive a consistent grammar

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0vk: i agree with the comment that the css grammar is rather hacky

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 104bc19e5513cba4eba2d18c7a704a01: if we think this is important, somebody should sit down and think about it

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: the grammar could be described in a snapshot

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0vk: the alterative is for MQ to define its own grammar, like the CSS selectors spec

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: steve: there are selveral pieces to this: all the bits are not meant to go into a grammar generator

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: fantasasi: the productions for one specific module is prefixed with an identifier specific to the module; if a production is intended to replace an existing one, this will be marked

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0 can either define a grammar for MQ or resolve the differences with the global grammar.

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: chrisl: somebody has to sit down and propose a solution

author: 04c6178a6b383efd09549f9028ece8b4
text: RESOLVED: e3fb62ebfa4f36acf5cbff6a6ed0f2e0 can choose to either define a grammar for MQ or resolve the differences with the global grammar

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: I don't think we have anything to discuss with namespaces, just need implementation reports

author: 3f21e54c5c5ffd50fe3680acc025bb1d
text: The test suite went through a very meticulous review process and has already been published.
